@startuml
title Creature Control System (a.k.a. Dungeon Master) Class Diagram

' Define styles to match the visual appearance of classes in the original diagram
skinparam class {
    BackgroundColor #F0F4FF
    BorderColor Black
}
skinparam noteBackgroundColor LightYellow
skinparam arrowFontSize 12
hide empty members

class Level_master <<C>> {
+ update(vector<player_input>* inputs) : void
- move_creatures(vector<player_input>* inputs) : void
# resolve_combat(Creature* attacker, Creature* defender) : bool
~ interact(Creature* creature, Interactible* tgt) : InteractionResult?
}

note top of Level_master 
Level_master is responsible for handling the logic of gameplay interactions between level objects e.g. creatures, interactivles, etc.\n\nLevel_master serves to separate concerns between gameplay interaction logic and tile data handling e.g. map generation, bounds checks etc.\n\nThat said, having "friend" classes is often an indication of bad design, so this is likely not the final solution. Will think some more on alternative solutions.
end note


abstract class Creature_AI <<C>> 

class Simple_AI <<C>> extends Creature_AI {}
class Ground_melee_AI <<C>> extends Creature_AI {}
class Ground_ranged_AI <<C>> extends Creature_AI {}
class Flying_melee_AI <<C>> extends Creature_AI {}
class Flying_ranged_AI <<C>> extends Creature_AI {}



interface Tile <<C>> 


interface Interactable <<C>> 



class Level_map <<C>> {
{field}- tiles : matrix<2,Tile*>  
{field}-creatures: vector<Creature*>  

get_creature(size_t x,size_t y)->Creature*   
 get_tile( size_tx ,size_ty )->constTile *    
   _interacable_(sizet_x,sizety)_>Interactable_ }  


